     <p><strong><p><em>Helen De Cruz, Wonderstruck: How Wonder and Awe Shape the Way We Think</em>, Princeton University Press, 2024, 232pp., $27.95 (hbk), ISBN 9780691232126.</p></strong></p>
     <p><strong>Reviewed by Taylor Carman, Barnard College</strong></p>
     <p>The experience of something like wonder or awe is arguably a fundamental part of what it is to be human, and it is for that reason that our concepts of wonder and awe may be doomed to do both less than and more than what we want them to do. Less, because their very specificity will fail to capture the depth and richness of the experience. More, because such concepts, just in virtue of being concepts, will suggest associations, inferences, hypotheses, and perhaps theories that make the experiences seem more sharply defined, more intelligible, and more manageable than they really are. What can we say about wonder that does not threaten to tip over into either a lyrical sigh of wonder itself or a somewhat...
